{"id":14880742,"mediaExerciseId":"ab818ea2-a7ac-4340-a63a-6a4cf8a95912","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612264,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":42,"solutions":[{"id":5898069,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to determine the reason why standard accounting practice focuses on historical cost rather than market value cost.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**Historical Cost** is a cost used in accounting in which the cost of an asset on the balance sheet is recorded at its original acquisition cost. While **market value** is the cost price currently offered for an asset or service in the market. \n\nCompanies focus on historical costs rather than market value costs in standard accounting practices because historical costs can be objectively and precisely measured. \n\nIn contrast, market value costs are difficult to estimate and sometimes unreasonable.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/be30a5b931c68946478b9e12ffb1f394/e3b1d910c634e04c8329b0c372272de1/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/17/be30a5b931c68946478b9e12ffb1f394/e3b1d910c634e04c8329b0c372272de1/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"969d42dd-5d62-4835-83b4-257c03e1b8e4","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2},{"id":5971963,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This question will explain why accounts appear as a cost rather than their market values in the balance sheet.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Following the Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP), entities should present financial statement line items at the actual amount received or paid for it. Expressly, accounting standards set that business should carry their balance sheet accounts at their **historical cost**.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":61,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/1b512906bbb059733233676533f022a1/986d9f85ec10b69313150026d0e36948/lateximg_large.png","width":994},"regular":{"height":32,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/1b512906bbb059733233676533f022a1/986d9f85ec10b69313150026d0e36948/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Presenting accounts at cost **maintains the reliability of financial statements** as values appear consistently across accounting periods. For instance, an entity can quickly determine the actual price of assets purchased years ago simply by looking at the balance sheet - creating a more straightforward comparison of current market prices of similar resources.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":138,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/1b512906bbb059733233676533f022a1/a0cc513be5452a486ddf0df4dc5ebb71/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":70,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/1b512906bbb059733233676533f022a1/a0cc513be5452a486ddf0df4dc5ebb71/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Additionally, the **cost principle** makes it easier for entities to present their accounts in financial statements. An item's actual cost or price is a more objective and accurate basis of its value - making current business reports comparable from previous years.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/1b512906bbb059733233676533f022a1/71c633711569f6581ea9e5c8c133c27a/lateximg_large.png","width":1029},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/31/1b512906bbb059733233676533f022a1/71c633711569f6581ea9e5c8c133c27a/lateximg.png","width":514}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"ab624fbe-2b0f-4c9c-a455-21e0cebff4f6","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14880743,"exerciseName":"4","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"a2a2189f-6fee-4411-8f79-b9a0e5dd5c93","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-4-a2a2189f-6fee-4411-8f79-b9a0e5dd5c93"},{"id":14880744,"exerciseName":"5","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"81a4bd65-9de3-4544-8568-bbed3057293d","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-5-81a4bd65-9de3-4544-8568-bbed3057293d"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14880741,"exerciseName":"2","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"733a1ef4-d083-4674-9e1c-9c2e8ac7f038","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-2-733a1ef4-d083-4674-9e1c-9c2e8ac7f038"},{"id":14880740,"exerciseName":"1","page":42,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"5d03328a-ad6f-4295-8608-d4c0bb984c32","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-1-5d03328a-ad6f-4295-8608-d4c0bb984c32"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-2-critical-thinking-questions-3-ab818ea2-a7ac-4340-a63a-6a4cf8a95912"}